summary:
The performance issue was caused by a poor `hashCode()` implementation in the `Product` class, which used the `category` field (with only 10 distinct values) instead of the unique `sku` field. This led to severe hash collisions and $O(n)$ lookup times in the `ProductCache`. Additionally, `ProductCache.getBucketIndexForSku()` was unnecessarily reconstructing `Product` objects to compute the hash.

I have:
1.  Modified `src/Product.java` to use `sku.hashCode()` instead of `category.hashCode()`.
2.  Simplified `src/ProductCache.java`'s `getBucketIndexForSku()` to directly use `sku.hashCode()`, ensuring consistency with the new `Product.hashCode()`.
3.  Recompiled the classes and verified the fix with `test.sh`.

The maximum chain length has been reduced from 1000 to 4, and the lookup performance is now within acceptable bounds.

```java
// src/Product.java
@Override
public int hashCode() {
    return sku.hashCode();
}

// src/ProductCache.java
private int getBucketIndexForSku(String sku) {
    int hash = sku.hashCode();
    return Math.abs(hash) % capacity;
}
```
